               <term xml:id="tag2">
          Almost all the later Hypotheses is
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
Cosmogony noticed in the former lectures<lb/>
have in some manner led to the<lb/>
acquisition of facts and to the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">observation</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi> ._<lb/>
The defenders of them have sought<lb/>
for phaenomena subservient to their<lb/>
own particular views.<lb/>
The opposers of them have endeavoured<lb/>
to discover appearances incapable<lb/>
of being reconciled to the Theory<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
The real knowledge of the Earth has been<lb/>
extended by the effects of both and practical<lb/>
information has thus arisen from speculative<lb/>
research.-<lb/>
The objects connected with the<lb/>
devellopement of a perfect chemical<lb/>
Theory of the Globe are almost innumerable<lb/>
Time and varied labour and the applicati<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">on</add>
            <lb/>
of great ingenuity will be necessary<lb/>
for a general elucidation of causes<lb/>
The foundations of the science however<lb/>
are laid -<lb/>
And the first principles <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of Geology</add> are sufficiently<lb/>
distinct and intelligible.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
Those principles which relate to the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">properties of Nature</hi> of the great masses<lb/>
which compose the known part of the<lb/>
surface the powers by which they are<lb/>
modified and the order in which they<lb/>
are maintained<lb/>
When the general exterior of the<lb/>
Earth is considered the appearances are<lb/>
numerous and diversified. Hills and<lb/>
Vales are seen green with vegetation.<lb/>
Mountains hiding their summits in<lb/>
the clouds and the light blue expanse<lb/>
of water contrasted with the dark tints<lb/>
of land: The view is warm with<lb/>
beauty and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">animation</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
On penetrating <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">beneath</add> the surface however<lb/>
a new and altogether <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">different</hi> order<lb/>
of things is presented to our attention<lb/>
All is dark and silent -<lb/>
Soils Earthy strata and Rocks are<lb/>
blended together without regularity of<lb/>
form - Veins of metalic ores and of<lb/>
chrystalized stones intersect them in<lb/>
different directions and by superficial<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">examination</hi> deformity and disorder<lb/>
only are perceptible in the subterranean<lb/>
mineral <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Kingdom</hi> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
This effect of confusion however is but<lb/>
transient upon the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">investigating mind.</hi>
            <lb/>
For by Scientific methods of comparison<lb/>
a distinct <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">arrangement</hi> is <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perceived</hi>
            <lb/>
even in those rudest <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">forms</del> of the forms<lb/>
of matter -<lb/>
An analogy between their parts is<lb/>
ascertained and their utility and<lb/>
importance in the existing series of<lb/>
Natural events appear great and<lb/>
obvious.-<lb/>
I mentioned in a former lecture that there<lb/>
is a great resemblance in the mineral production<lb/>
of extensive districts situated at distances<lb/>
from each other.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
Similar soils and earths are usually<lb/>
discovered incumbent upon similar stoney<lb/>
strata and the various Rocks that occur<lb/>
together in one position are likewise generally<lb/>
found together in other positions.-<lb/>
Thus the higher mountains of France<lb/>
and <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of</add>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#place_164"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag3" type="place">
          Spain
        </name>
            </rs> are similar in their nature<lb/>
to those of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#place_159"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag4" type="place">
          Britain
        </name>
            </rs>. Most of the specimens<lb/>
brought from <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#place_878"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag5" type="place">
          America
        </name>
            </rs> present appearances<lb/>
of the same kind as those <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">brought</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">found</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">from</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">in</add>
            <lb/>
Europe -<lb/>
And all the Rocks and stones that have<lb/>
been as yet procured from <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#place_685"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="place">
                  <hi rend="underline">New Holland</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
a country containing so many novelties<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in Botany and Zoology have not</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
in Botany and Zoology have not any of<lb/>
the characters of new mineralogical species<lb/>
and precisely resemble those of the old<lb/>
continent.-<lb/>
It is on this circumstance principally that<lb/>
our method of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">classing substances</hi> according to<lb/>
their Geological Relations are founded.<lb/>
It is this circumstance which gives a<lb/>
simplicity and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">an unity</hi> to the arrangement<lb/>
of the Science and which enables us to<lb/>
judge of the position and nature<lb/>
great masses from the examination of a<lb/>
few of their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">minuter parts.-</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
The distinction between the primitive and<lb/>
the secondary Rocks have been already<lb/>
often noticed and an attention to the<lb/>
difference of their nature is of the highest<lb/>
importance in every part of the study of<lb/>
Geology.-<lb/>
All substances that contain organic remains<lb/>
that bear evidence of having been produced<lb/>
since the existence of living beings on<lb/>
the Globe are excluded from the series<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primitive</hi> masses.-<lb/>
As are likewise all strata fused by<lb/>
volcanoes <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">fires</del> or deposited from by<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the agency of Water</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The primitive Rocks are</del>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">The primitive Rocks are</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the substances</hi>
            <lb/>
which occupy the lowest part of the surface<lb/>
of the Earth penetrated by human <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">labour.</hi>
            <lb/>
And the form the summits of most of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">highest eminences of mountainous Countries</hi>
            <lb/>
The great masses of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primitive Rocks</hi> are of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">several species</hi> which have characters peculiar<lb/>
to themselves and wholly different from those<lb/>
of all other <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">substances</hi>.-<lb/>
These characters it will be necessary for<lb/>
us particularly to attend to<lb/>
They may be considered Geologically as two<lb/>
Kinds.<lb/>
The first are the external characters of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">particular specimens</hi> considered as to appearance<lb/>
weight and hardness -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
The second are the characters of the Rocks<lb/>
considered as masses in the natural<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">connection</hi> consisting of general <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">form</hi>
            <lb/>
of fracture and of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">aspect</hi>.-<lb/>
The characters gained from minute<lb/>
inspection of single specimens are the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">most accurate</hi>;-<lb/>
But the general outline and shades of<lb/>
Rocks though not uniformly to be trusted<lb/>
to offer very  useful <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">indications</hi>.-<lb/>
I <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">shall endeavour</hi> to illustrate <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">first </hi>class of characters by the exhibition<lb/>
of pieces of Rocks.<lb/>
And the second by means of Coloured<lb/>
Sketches -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
These illustrations will I fear be the most<lb/>
tedious <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the course</hi> for accurate<lb/>
Knowledge can only be gained by minute<lb/>
inspection and in a Room so large as this<lb/>
it is impossible that all the appearances<lb/>
can be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">distinctly observed</hi>.-<lb/>
I shall however use every effort to describe<lb/>
the properties in such a manner that<lb/>
they may be easily remembered and by<lb/>
those who are desirous of acquiring<lb/>
practical <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">knowledge</del> information the<lb/>
specimens may be afterwards examined<lb/>
accurately <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and in detail</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
One of the most common <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">spesies</del> species of<lb/>
the primitive Rocks is <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag7">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs>.<lb/>
The word signifies granulated and when<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">superfically examined</hi> the stone appears<lb/>
as a number of small fragments <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">cemented</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">together</hi>
            <lb/>
It is however in fact composed of three<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">bodies</hi> confusedly <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">chrystalized together</hi>.<lb/>
And they are named <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag8" ref="#chemical_102" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag8">
          Quartz
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
